'''Kokuzō Shrine''' (こくぞうじんじゃ / くにのみやつこじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Teno, Ichinomiya-machi, {{ill|lt=Aso|Q733681|qid=Q733681|1=Aso, Kumamoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kumamoto Prefecture|Q130308|qid=Q130308|1=Kumamoto Prefecture}}. Because it stands north of former kanpei-taisha {{ill|lt=Aso Shrine|Q715639|qid=Q715639|1=Aso Shrine}}, it is also called '''Kita-no-Miya'''. It is an {{ill|lt=Engishiki shikinaisha|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} and its former rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref>{{ill|lt=Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun|Q11568194|qid=Q11568194|1=Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun}} (ed.), ''Kumamoto Prefecture Encyclopedia'', 1982, p.375</ref>.

=== History and origin ===
The {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} lists four shrines in {{ill|lt=Higo Province|Q259705|qid=Q259705|1=Higo Province}} (Takeiwatatsu-no-Mikoto Shrine = present {{ill|lt=Aso Shrine|Q715639|qid=Q715639|1=Aso Shrine}}, Asohime Shrine = present Aso Shrine, Kokuzō Shrine, and {{ill|lt=Hikino Shrine|Q17224057|qid=Q17224057|1=Hikino Shrine}}). Kokuzō Shrine is one of these four and is one of the oldest shrines in Kumamoto Prefecture. According to ''Higo no Kuni-shi'', in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|qid=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}, Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto was appointed Higo no Kuni no Miyatsuko, and in {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|qid=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}} 18 ({{ill|lt=88 CE|Q24844|qid=Q24844|1=AD 88}}), Kokuzō Shrine was repaired and rituals were organized<ref>''Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei 44: Place Names of Kumamoto Prefecture'', Heibonsha, 1985, p.310</ref>.

With his father, Aso Shrine's principal deity {{ill|lt=Takeiwatatsu-no-Mikoto|Q10888904|qid=Q10888904|1=Takeiwatatsu-no-Mikoto}}, he is said to have developed the Aso area and taught agriculture and afforestation. The principal deity is '''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}''' (according to ''{{ill|lt=Kokuzō Hongi|Q133833194|qid=Q133833194|1=Kokuzo Hongi}}'', the first '''{{ill|lt=Aso Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q56347021|qid=Q56347021|1=Aso Kuni no Miyatsuko}}'''), and together with his consort and sons, four deities are enshrined<ref>Editorial Committee of Kadokawa Place Names Dictionary (ed.), ''Kadokawa Place Names Dictionary 43 Kumamoto Prefecture'', Kadokawa Shoten, 1987, p.481</ref>.

The current shrine buildings were built in {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 12 ({{ill|lt=1672|Q7614|qid=Q7614|1=1672}}) by {{ill|lt=Hosokawa Tsunatoshi|Q11605971|qid=Q11605971|1=Hosokawa Tsunatoshi}}, third lord of the {{ill|lt=Kumamoto Domain|Q1194248|qid=Q1194248|lt=Higo Kumamoto Domain|1=Kumamoto Domain}}<ref>Kadokawa Place Names Dictionary 43 Kumamoto Prefecture, Kadokawa Shoten, 1987, p.1297</ref>. It became a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in Meiji 5.

About 60 m west of the torii are the '''Kamimikura Kofun''', regarded as the tomb of the enshrined deity Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto, and the '''Shimomikura Kofun''', regarded as the tomb of his consort Amiya-hime-no-Mikoto. These are late-6th-century {{ill|lt=round kofun|Q11394747|qid=Q11394747|1=Round Kofun}} with {{ill|lt=horizontal stone chambers|Q11543435|qid=Q11543435|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber}}, built of huge {{ill|lt=andesite|Q181908|qid=Q181908|1=Andesite}} blocks and cut Aso lava stone, and are representative megalithic kofun of Kumamoto.

=== Teno no Sugi ===
[[ファイル:Tenonosugi.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Preserved remains of Teno no Sugi]]
A giant cedar known as "{{ill|lt=Teno no Sugi|Q17217752|qid=Q17217752|1=Teno No Sugi}}" once stood in the precincts<ref name="Natural monument encyclopedia 116">''Natural Monument Encyclopedia'', p.116.</ref><ref name="Japan natural monuments 151">''Natural Monuments of Japan'', p.151.</ref>. It was designated a national natural monument on December 9, 1924, under the then Historic Sites, Places of Scenic Beauty and Natural Monuments Preservation Law<ref>Ministry of Home Affairs Notice No. 777, Taishō 13</ref>. It broke in Typhoon No. 19 (the "Apple Typhoon") on September 27, 1991, and in 2000 the Council for Cultural Affairs recommended de-designation<ref name="Natural monument encyclopedia 116"/><ref name="Japan natural monuments 151"/><ref name="de-designation (Agency for Cultural Affairs)">[https://web.archive.org/web/20060111191246/http://www.bunka.go.jp/1hogo/main.asp%7B0fl=show&id=1000007342&clc=1000011213&cmc=1000007006&cli=1000007317&cmi=1000007325%7B9.html Historic Sites / Scenic Places / Natural Monuments (May 2000)] Agency for Cultural Affairs website, viewed 2013-06-10.</ref>, and it was officially de-designated on September 6, 2000<ref>Ministry of Education Notice No. 150, 2000</ref>.

{{Main|Teno no Sugi}}

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto - son of Aso Shrine principal deity Takeiwatatsu-no-Mikoto. Aso Kuni no Miyatsuko Ōkami. Enshrined at the 11th shrine of Aso Shrine.
* Amiya-hime-no-Mikoto - consort of Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto. Also called Kamachi-hime-no-Mikoto; sea deity goddess. Principal deity of {{ill|lt=Kōriura Shrine|Q11643225|qid=Q11643225|1=Konoura Shrine}}.
* Takahashi-no-Kami - second son of Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto.
* Hinomiya-no-Kami - third son of Hayamikatama-no-Mikoto.

=== Annual festival day ===
* July 26

